review_blob:
330ml bottle from Brewdog. Pours ruby brown with thin white head and decent lacing. 

Aroma is lovely. Full of pine, with nuts, raisins, citrus and dark caramel. Taste is dry, gently bitter, with background sweetness. Body is thin for the ABV with a medium and roasty finish.

Pretty good brown ale.
beer_name: Brew By Numbers 09/05 Brown Ale - Chinook & Centennial

review_blob:
Bottle from Brewdog. Pours a cloudy orange with a persistent clean white head and good lacing.

Aroma is clean, fruity and hoppy. I can see why they describe it as juicy! Theres classic Citra aromas with lemon, mango, pineapple, tangerine, fresh grass, lemongrass and a very faint caramel. Taste is sweet, but not cloying, with bitterness towards the end. Surprisingly light body and a lovely long finish.

Very smooth and drinkable for 9%, but was expecting something more dramatic.

Pours a lager yellow with centimetre of clean white head and lively carbonation.

Aroma is pineapple, lemon, pine, melon, straw, lime and light clean malt. Taste is quite bitter with sweetness amid an impressive medium to long finish. A touch watery but its all about the hops in this one.

Decent and drinkable pale ale.

Pours a hazy yellow to orange with a thin white head, soft carbonation and a touch of lacing.

Aroma is marmelade, mango, lemon and a nice light caramel. Taste is quite bitter with a nice mouthfeel from the wheat and decent body for the ABV accompanied with a good medium finish.

All in all, pleasant and drinkable pale ale.

330ml from their bottleshop. Pours a hazy yellow to amber with lively carbonation and white head with touch of lacing.

Aromas are orange, cloves, black pepper, ripe banana, straw, raisin and light caramel. Taste is quite sweet, with slight sour notes from the yeast and a good length finish.

Decent and interesting wheat beer thats very drinkable.

330ml from their bottleshop. Pours a lively black with slight tan coloured head and frothy head with good lacing.

Aroma is promising, with citrus, pine, coffee, nettles and bitter chocolate notes. Taste is quite sweet with some bitterness in a salty finish. A little thin, but in line with the low ABV.

A decent low strength hoppy porter.
beer_name: London Beer Lab Flavourly Lab Porter

review_blob:
330ml from their bottle shop. Pours golden amber with dense white head, good lacing and medium carbonation.

Aroma is pineapple, lemon, grassy, white bread. Taste is quite bitter with some sweetness in the background and a nice fizz on the tongue amid a medium finish.

Nice.
beer_name: London Beer Lab Tip Top Citra

review_blob:
500ml bottle from the brewery. Pours a hazy yellow to amber with a white head and mild carbonation, just like all their other pale ale!

Aroma is pineapple, apple, straw, light caramel, bread, thyme, white pepper, marmelade and lime. Taste has nice bitterness, just about enough body if verging on thin and some sweetness.

Delivers just as expected, very decent pale ale showcasing two of my favourite hops!
beer_name: The Kernel Pale Ale Citra Centennial

review_blob: UPDATED: APR 25, 2016

500ml bottle from Kernel bottleshop. Pours yellow, with small white head and mild carbonation.

Aroma is pretty good considering the ABV. Mango, pineapple, lemon, lime. Nice bitterness on the taste and finish. Understandably thin but refreshing.

Impressive to get those aromas into a 3% beer, even if it lacks body. Good one on a hot day to quench your thirst.

Bottle from Kernel shop. Pours hazy yellow to amber with a white head, mild carbonation and decent lacing.

Aroma is strong pineapple, pine, lemon, marmelade, with light caramel in the background. Medium body, sweet fruitness and a medium finish. 

As pronounced a pineapple flavour as Ive had and pretty decent if not my favourite of their IPA hop mixes.
beer_name: The Kernel India Pale Ale Simcoe Sticklebract

review_blob:
Bottle from Kernel brewery.

Pours black to dark brown with a tan head, mild carbonation and decent lacing.

Aroma is nice and hoppy with the roast malts coming through when in the mouth. Pine, citrus, dark caramel, mint, dark chocolate and black coffee. Taste is bitter, with rich sweetness and salt on the finish, but doesnt live up to the aroma. Finish is medium if shorter than expected, roasty and good for the ABV. 

Decent dry stout. Dare I say it, Guinness with proper aroma (other stouts are available!).

From the Kernel bottleshop. Pours hazy yellow to amber with mild carbonation and thin white head and decent lacing.

Aroma is mango, orange peel, lemon, bread and light caramel with a hint of soap from that Citra. Taste is sweet with decent bitterness and a pleasant medium finish with plenty of body.

Classic Kernel IPA, very decent brew.
beer_name: The Kernel India Pale Ale Citra Nelson Sauvin Galaxy

review_blob:
From the brewery bottle shop. Pours a hazy yellow to amber with thick white head and mild carbonation

Aroma is hoppy pine, ripe apple, lemon, lime, pineapple, with light caramel and hint of soap from that Citra. Taste is quite sweet, some bitterness and a medium finish with light to medium body.

Just a classic Kernel Pale Ale really. Have had better ones, but its very drinkable.
beer_name: The Kernel Pale Ale Cascade Citra Simcoe

review_blob:
Pours amber brown with slight cloudiness and plenty of carbonation. Consistent thick white head.

Aroma is not that pleasant with a soapy note coming through amid the pine, honey, mint and orange peel. Its sweet although there is bitterness there as well, but not enough to balance it out. Hint of booze on the nose, but its watery for its ABV and has a slightly unpleasant aftertaste. 

If I hadnt had this a few times before Id think this one was a dud that was over-oxygenated. At least its consistent! I want to like this given its availability and origins, but its a real disappointment.

Pours dark brown to black with yellow head which was lively but quick to disappear. Some lacing.

Aroma is promising with smoke, chocolate, raisin, liquorice and dark caramel. Taste is quite bitter with residual sweetness and a sour note at the finish. Let down by its medium body.

Decent smoked porter, just wish theyd upped the ABV a little to get more body in there.

Pours a hazy yellow to pale amber. Clean white head, low carbonation and good lacing.

Was a little cold from the fridge which affected the aroma, but theres plenty there all the same. Mango, pineapple, lemon and a good malt and bready backbone. Less in your face hoppy aromas than I was expecting. Plenty of body and nicely balanced with sweetness there and a lovely long fruity, malty finish.

Very decent beer and certainly doesnt taste the near 9% on the tin.

Pours amber with a white quickly fading head with light to medium carbonation.

Aroma is pine, orange peel, grassy, lemon and caramel. Flavour is nicely balanced mix of sweetness and gentle bitterness, with a medium finish.

Started with low expectations, but very pleasantly surprised. OK, Id prefer a punchy pale ale, but this is really good flavoursome lager and slipped down a treat.

Pours dark brown to black with yellow brown head that fades, good lacing and medium carbonation.

Aroma is lovely - citrus hops, dark caramel, ash, cream, pine. Taste doesnt quite match the aroma - its silky smooth, sweet, some bitterness with a medium finish.

Decent Black IPA/Porter hybrid given the ABV.

Bottle from M&S.; Poured a cloudy orange yellow and bizarrely had some black bits floating around which does not look good at all and suggests problems with the brew. 

Citrus orange, gratefruit, lemon, pine and caramel. Taste is bready, bitter, medium sweet with plenty of unfermentables in there and touch of sourness probably from the wheat. Quite smooth mouthfeel but a touch medicinal.

Had promise, but not the best quality control.
beer_name: By The Horns Wolfie Smith Amber IPA

review_blob:
Pours dark brown to black with a thick yellow head and good lacing.

Aroma once warmed up a little was ash, coffee, toffee, dark chocolate, raisin and hazelnut. Taste is oily, reasonable body, quite sweet and gentle bitterness, with ash and toffee lingering in a medium finish.

Not bad porter and balanced, just could be a lot more exciting for that ABV.

Pours copper with thin white head, medium carbonation and some lacing.

Aroma is citrus, caramel, honey, mint, orange peel and lots of pine. Flavour is very bitter, medium sweet and the mother of all finishes, just keeps going and going (and going), with some booziness at the end to remind you youre drinking 9% ale!

Nothing subtle about this one - dangerously drinkable... For once, lives up to the Brewdog hype on the label.

Good looking beer - pours dark brown to black with off white to yellow head and nice lacing.

Aroma is promising - hybrid of stout and IPA mostly works. Dont serve this one too cold or will miss most of it. Theres pine, dark caramel, ash, mint, raisin, milky coffee and tangerine, but a touch metallic. Taste is smooth, quite bitter, decent body and sweetness, with a touch of booze in the medium finish.

Stout and IPA fairly evenly matched in there, with IPA more on the nose, stout more on the finish. Nice beer - would like to try an imperial version of this!

Pours copper to brown with quick disappearing head with mild carbonation. 

Beer was a little too cold as the aroma was quite mild until it warmed up a little and then started to come alive. 

Theres dark caramel, lemon, lime, orange peel, pine, wood and raisin. The taste is quite bitter, with sweetness later and a nice medium to long finish and a hint of booze right at the end, although less than youd expect given the 7%.

Was expecting more pronounced rye and hop flavours - usual Brewdog over-hyping (if you call it squid assassin, then you expect something pretty punchy!) - but its a good beer nonetheless.

Pours lager pale yellow with medium carbonation and disappearing head.

Good strong smell of citrus, with plenty of gratefruit, kiwi, lemon, herbs and some straw in there. It certainly is bitter, too bitter, but theres also sweetness in there and a long bitter citrus finish which is OK, but not that pleasant. A hint of booze on the finish is nice. Was hoping for more malt and body given the ABV.

Its good, but a little disappointed with this one. Fair play to them though for chucking everything at it to make a distinctive beer.

Good looking beer, pours black to dark brown with good lacing and creamy yellow head.

Aroma is interesting mix of classic US hops with citrus, pine, coriander and dark caramel, dark fruit malts. Taste is bitter, sweet with a nice harsh note in there. Only let down by slightly thin and small to medium finish.

Very decent beer. For once lives up to the usual over-hyped deScription from Brewdog!

Pours copper brown with medium white head and good lacing and soft carbonation.

Aroma is restrained considering what theyve chucked at this. Fruity with tangerine, caramel, orange, lime. Taste is bitter, sweet, earthy, a hint of sourness with a medium slightly metallic finish. Quite thin.

Improved when it warmed up, but a little disappointed with this one. Brewdog - stop over-hyping your beers!

Pours copper t brown with a thin off-white head.

Aroma is reasonably hoppy mix of mango, caramel, tangerine, orange peel and mint. Some bitterness and sweetness with a lingering thin finish. 

It may be thin but its very decent low alcohol beer - just try the competition!
UPDATED: FEB 21, 2016

Pours dark brown to black with a thin yellowy head and light carbonation.

Aroma is chocolate, liquorice, caramel, hint of coffee, toffee, wood, all quite subtle. Taste delivers beyond the aroma - its very sweet, almost cloying, with a touch of salt on a medium finish and reasonable body for the ABV.

Delivered what it promised - dessert in a glass. Slipped down a treat. A couple more points on the ABV to get more body and a hint of booze and this would be cracking stuff. Id love to have an imperial version of this!

Pours dark brown to black with an off-white thin to medium head and subtle carbonation.

Aroma isnt the best with some plastic, liquorice, peaty, dark caramel notes, with very light spice. Taste is thin, bitter with a slightly medicinal finish.

Not one of their best and certainly didnt live up to the over-hyped billing.

Pours yellow, almost lager like with white head and mild carbonation.

Aroma is lighter and more subtle than I was expecting, with citrus, tropical, straw, pine, classic US hop combos. Taste delivers more than the aroma with a nice malt backbone, gentle bitterness and decent range of flavours. Light medium thin finish.

Was expecting a bold US session IPA whereas this is more subtle and balanced and pleasant enough.

Pours red with fast disappearing head and no carbonation to speak of. Must be the raspberries.

Plenty of raspberry aroma, some lemon and not much else. Sweet, sour and tart on the taste with a medium finish.

Not the kind of beer I like, more alcopop than beer, but you can tell its well executed all the same.

Pours pale amber with good lacing and persistent white head.

Aroma is more muted than I expected, with caramel, some citrus and soapy notes, but definitely no hop bomb. Flavour is sweet, malty, some bitterness with short to medium finish.

Little disappointed with this given the high ratings on here. Wonder if may have been past its best

Pours copper with a persistent thick white head.

Aroma is nice, with tangerine, dates, ripe plum and the rye background. Not sure what hops have been used but there are Bramling Cross and other classic English hop tones which are very pleasant. Taste has bitterness, with a decent sweet medium finish which is a touch thin for the ABV and malt bill.

Pretty good. Kudos to M&S; for commissioning craft brews.

Pours amber to orange with thin head and little carbonation.

Aroma is full of orange peel, with some floral, coriander spice notes and caramel malt in the background. The American hops are somewhat lost in the additives. Taste is bitter, with a thin, slightly oily short finish.

Quite an unusual hybrid of some wheat beer flavours (no wheat according to the label!) and IPA. Nice but not really sure it works.

Pours slightly hazy yellow to amber with lively carbonation.

Aroma is promising - classic US hop with citrus, pine with nice caramel and wheat malt coming through. Taste is bitter and quite sweet. A little thin but not bad given the ABV.

Nice little session ale, nicely balanced letting you taste all the ingredients.

Pours dark brown to black with a thin off white head.

Aroma is nice. Coffee, ash, liquorice, dark chocolate, with some citrus and mint from the hops. Taste doesnt live up to the aroma and is thin with no real finish to speak of.

OK, but nothing special.

Pours dark black with yellow creamy head with light carbonation.

Aroma is classic porter with ash, plum, dark fruit, caramel, oats, touch of mint. Taste is bitter, salty and sweet. Medium bitter oily and smooth finish with nice hint of booze, if a little cloying.

Solid porter. Little too much salt and ash flavours in there to my taste.

Pours black with yellow oily head and just enough carbonation on the tongue.

Aroma is coffee, ash, chocolate, milk, dark fruit, raisin but plenty of hop there as well with mint, nettles and hay. Not overpowering, but complex and full of promise. 

Lovely smooth rich bitter and long complex finish with a touch of booze. Impressive.
Spot on. Can taste the NZ hops, background pale malt, nice bit of booze. Job done.
beer_name: The Kernel India Pale Ale Nelson Sauvin Victoria Secret

review_blob:
Citra IPA, whats not to like?

Pours yellow to amber with little carbonation or head.

Classic citra in the nose if a little toned down for the ABV. Citrus, grass, tropical, lemon. Touch of soap and medicinal notes suggest its nearly there but not quite executed. Pale malt comes through, with decent body and lovely boozy finish.

Very close to excellent with my favourite hop but not quite.

Pours pale yellow with white foam.

Aroma is lemon, hay, grass, lime, wheat, banana. Flavour is slightly funky & sour, thin, no real malt and short finish. 

Refreshing and some interest with the funky yeast but not one of my favourites.
beer_name: The Kernel Biere de Table Fresh Hop - Progress

review_blob:
Pours dark copper brown with yellow head.

Not much of an aroma - certainly not the porter aromas I was expecting or even a whiff of strong caramel. Some dark fruit, marshmallow, soap, orange peel.

Finish is thin, background of dark caramel, hint of chocolate and salt in there, but disappointingly little.

Great idea, poorly executed. This should be thick, dark, indulgent, but is none of those things. Shame.
beer_name: Marks & Spencer Maritime Salted Caramel Porter

review_blob:
Pours amber to copper with foamy cream head. Mid-carbonation, clear and very nice to look at.

Aroma is good, but was expecting more hop aroma. Lots of pine, orange peel, floral, mint. Quite sweet and full finish.

Very nice, but not sure its much of a step up from the standard Sierra Nevada Pale. Got better the further I got down the glass, so temperature may be a factor - was only lightly chilled.

Pours a cloudy yellow with white foamy head and minimal carbonation.

Aroma is all American hops - lemony citrus, pine, floral with a pleasant malt backbone. Light finish and a touch thin.

Decent session IPA.

Pours a dark brown with yellow slight head which quickly faded.

Aroma of coffee, liquorice, raisin, touch of clove & cinnamon spice but unfortunately also a strong whiff of chlorine and metal. Flavour is bitter, salty, surprisingly thin and, ew, chlorinated. Classic off-flavours from phenols. 

Maybe a bad bottle from a change in the water from rain which affected the water treatment? Surely theyre not all like this...

Bottle. Pours black with no head at all or carbonation.

Aroma is ash, tar, coffee, plum, raisin, cinnamon, clove and blackcurrant. Flavour is bitter, a touch sour, with a boozy, oily finish that is a little thin considering its strength.

Its hard to dislike a well brewed imperial stout, but Ive definitely had much better ones.
beer_name: Gadds Imperial Russian Stout Brettanomyces Lambicus 2012

review_blob:
500ml bottle. Pours pale amber, clear, with persistant white head.

Aroma is full on East Kent Goldings, with marmelade, honey, pine, grassy and floral but more pronounced than on a usual Kentish ale given the green hops. A touch thin but nicely hop forward. Some sweetness and a decent bitter finish.

Pretty good for this style of beer.

Bottle. Pours dark black with quickly disappearing yellow oily yellow head and just a hint of carbonation. 

Aroma is boozy, dark fruit, liquorice, tobacco, touch of ash. Flavour has plenty of oats coming through and a reasonably smooth and long, pretty boozy finish.

Its very decent, but a touch unbalanced.
